passages.text: Apres moi la bruine legere

We are not overly concerned by French political risk, and do not see it derailing the current tight spread and low volatility environment. On an unadjusted basis, the EUR IG benchmark is trading 7bp wide to USD IG, the widest differential in two months. The France 'premium' increased by 2bp, and has been tracking the OAT- Bund differential closely. Our Financials team put out several trade ideas on French banks (see here). We provide a summary of the eligibility criteria for the new European Defence Bond Label from Euronext.

The market tone softened this week, with investment grade and high yield widening by 3bp and 11bp, respectively. In our view, this was primarily driven by French political risk. OAT- Bund spreads have widened by 13bp since the local tights in mid- Aug, briefly reaching their widest level since January, after Prime Minister Bayrou called a Vote of No Confidence on \(8^{\text{th}}\) September. The leadership of National Rally, the Socialists, and the Greens have all announced that they will vote against the government, and our economists' base case is that Bayrou is unlikely to survive the vote (see here).

With that said, we see little reason for it to derail the current tight spread and low volatility environment in credit markets. Primarily, there is still plenty of room for negotiation and compromise, even if it could be messy and may require a new administration. The government is currently targeting a \(0.9\% - \text{pt}\) fiscal adjustment in the 2026 budget, which is larger than the \(0.5\% - \text{pt}\) adjustment required by the European Commission to comply with the fiscal ruleset (see here). Further, the package includes politically unpopular measures such as scrapping two bank holidays. Consequently, even if Bayrou is ejected, it seems viable for Macron to nominate another centrist Prime Minister with a less ambitious tightening program, rather than calling for a new lower house election.

Further, a significant amount of political risk is already priced in with OATs trading wider than SGBs (Figure 1 and Figure 2). This premium may persist until France has a more stable government, or has at least passed a 2026 budget, with our rates colleagues looking for OAT- Bund spreads to trade in the 75 - 85bp range over the near term (see here). However, given that the government is making an attempt to be fiscally conservative, and there is still plenty of room for compromise with opposition parties, there is not the sense of 'crisis' at this stage which would justify credit spreads moving much wider. Europe has plenty of experience with much more concerning situations - from a fiscal standpoint - such as the election of Syriza in Greece in 2015 or Five Stars in Italy in 2018, who both ran on explicitly anti- austerity platforms. The lesson from these examples is that the EU fiscal framework has always won in the end.

Notably, EUR IG underperformed against USD IG again this week, which saw almost unchanged spreads (Figure 3 and Figure 4). Since the start of the month, the unadjusted differential between the benchmarks has gone from zero to 7bp, the widest in two months since the early summer. In our view, this potentially opens room for some outperformance of euros going forward.
Figure 3: EUR and USD IG Spreads, bp
Source: J.P. Morgan, S&P Globals
Figure 4: EUR - USD IG Spread Differential, bp
Source: J.P. Morgan.

French issuers unsurprisingly underperformed, widening by 5bp on the week, driven primarily by French banks with BNP and SocGen Bail- In generically 9- 11bp wider (Figure 5 and Figure 6). This took the France 'premium' to 7bp, closely tracking the move in OAT- Bund spreads, although with a much lower beta. Our Financials analysts put out a spotlight on French banks this week, including several trade ideas focused on T2 and AT1 (see here).

This week saw the first bond issued under the European Defence Bond Label (EDBL), with a €750mm deal from BPCE. This is a voluntary label developed by Euronext for bonds whose proceeds are ringfenced to support the Defence & Security sector (see here). In a broader context, this new label will support the rearmament of the region under the Readiness 2030 plan and commitments at the 2025 NATO Summit in the The Hague for Allies to invest \(5\%\) of GDP annually on Defence and Security by 2035 (see here and here).
Below, we provide a condensed summary of the eligibility criteria for the EDBL. The full criteria can be found on the Euronext website (see here):

- Must be either headquartered, incorporated, or generate more than \(50\%\) of revenues, capex, opex or payroll expenses in either the EU, EEA, or a country with either a formal cooperation agreement with the EU, a bilateral defence partnership, or active EU accession negotiations.- If used for project financing, \(85\%\) of net proceeds must be allocated to projects which contribute to the development, support or deployment of European Defence & Security capabilities.- Alternatively, if used for GCP, the issuer must generate more than \(50\%\) of revenue from Defence & Security activities.

- Must be either headquartered, incorporated, or operate under the regulatory framework of either the EU, EEA, or a country with either a formal cooperation agreement with the EU, a bilateral defence partnership, or active EU accession negotiations.- Proceeds must be used to finance European Defence and Security-related assets, meeting the specific definition under the label, or certain export and import operations.- Must have documented processes to assess eligibility and ensure traceability of proceeds allocation. Where granular quantitative data does not exist, they must have
a documented internal process to assess eligibility, relying on credible sources like industry lists, sectoral associations, defence registers, and classification frameworks.

·Eligible activities include, but are not limited to: research, development, and industrialization of defence systems; manufacturing and integration of military equipment; upgrades and modernization of existing military systems; cyber defence and secure communication systems; surveillance and intelligence systems;development of critical infrastructure for defence resilience; military logistics and operational support; dual-use projects with strategic security purposes; space and satellite infrastructure for secure communications; civil protection and crisis response capabilities; and services directly enabling defence capabilities.
·Exclusions include: companies involved in prohibited weapons, entities under sanctions regimes, and activities not compliant with international humanitarian law.

Our top trade portfolio was essentially unchanged this week, with two small gains, one small loss, and two positions flat. On the upside, our iTraxx Main 60 - 75bp Sep payer spread gained +1c, and our 1-3y BBB vs 7-10y BBB trade also gained +1c. On the other hand, cyclicals modestly compressed against non-cyclicals. Our OW A vs BBB and OW BB vs B positions were flat.

Flows remained positive this week, picking up marginally from last week's pace on the IG side, with funds attracting another €765mm over the week as redemptions from ETFs slowed and flows into all other categories picked up. HY funds also took in +€125mm, although that was the slowest weekly intake since late April. Strategic funds, meanwhile, saw a nearly €600mm subscription led primarily by total return mandates. Overall, however, the volume of fund inflows has downshifted in recent weeks from the pace set in June and July.

Figure 8: Weekly Fund Flows - High Yield & Strategic, €mm

Against this backdrop, the resurgence of primary deals did start to weigh on the market as investment grade corporates brought in €23bn, in the busiest week for supply since mid- May - this takes the month's total to €40bn, the second busiest August ever after last year's €44bn.
Figure 9: European Credit Supply, €bn
Source: J.P. Morgan, Bloomberg Finance L.P. Reporting week Fri - Thurs.
Book coverage ratios for the deals indicated the higher strain that technicals are facing at the moment, with the 20- deal median falling to 2x, at its lowest level since early 2024 (Figure 10).

While the average for all the deals that came through this month has stayed at a healthy \(3.2x\) , it's worth noting that nearly 2/3rds of the cohort priced with order-books lower than this ratio, with the average coverage for the bottom half of the list at just \(1.8x\) (Figure 11).
Figure 10: EUR IG Book Coverage Ratios, x
Figure 11: Distribution of Coverage Ratios - August 2025
Consequently, new issue concessions have started creeping up although remaining on average at low single- digit levels on a 20- deal lookback basis, at 5.3bp for corporates and 4bp for financials.

Figure 13: New Issue Premium - Euro IG Financials, bps

J.P. Morgan uses a bond- level rating system that incorporates valuations (relative value) and our fundamental view on the security. Our fundamental credit view of an issuer is based on the company's underlying credit trends, overall creditworthiness and our opinion on whether the issuer will be able to service its debt obligations when they become due and payable. We analyze, among other things, the company's cash flow capacity and trends and standard credit ratios, such as gross and net leverage, interest coverage and liquidity ratios. We also analyze profitability, capitalization and asset quality, among other variables, when assessing financials. Analysts also rate the issuer, based on the rating of the benchmark or representative security. Unless we specify a different recommendation for the company's individual securities, an issuer recommendation applies to all of the bonds at the same level of the issuer's capital structure. We may also rate certain loans and preferred securities, as applicable. This report also sets out within it the material underlying assumptions used. We use the following ratings for bonds (issues), issuers, loans, and preferred securities: Overweight (over the next three months, the recommended risk position is expected to outperform the relevant index, sector, or benchmark); Neutral (over the next three months, the recommended risk position is expected to perform in line with the relevant index, sector, or benchmark); and Underweight (over the next three months, the recommended risk position is expected to underperform the relevant index, sector, or benchmark). J.P. Morgan Emerging Markets Sovereign Research uses Marketweight, which is equivalent to Neutral. NR is Not Rated. In this case, J.P. Morgan has removed the rating for this particular security or issuer because of either a lack of a sufficient fundamental basis or for legal, regulatory or policy reasons. The previous rating no longer should be relied upon. An NR designation is not a recommendation or a rating. NC is Not Covered. An NC designation is not a rating or a recommendation. For CDS, we use the following rating system: Long Risk (over the next three months, the credit return on the recommended position is expected to exceed the relevant index, sector or benchmark); Neutral (over the next three months, the credit return on the recommended position is expected to match the relevant index, sector or benchmark); and Short Risk (over the next three months, the credit return on the recommended position is expected to underperform the relevant index, sector or benchmark).
